properties.name: Schwabing-West
properties.Description:
Schwabing-West (District 4)
A trendy and bohemian neighborhood north of the city center.
•	Former home to artists and writers like Wassily Kandinsky and Thomas Mann
•	Features beautiful Jugendstil (Art Nouveau) architecture
•	Home to many students and young professionals
•	Offers numerous cafes, bars, and boutique shops
Schwabing-West is perfect for those seeking a lively, artistic atmosphere

properties.name: Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt
properties.Description:
Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt (District 2)
A vibrant and diverse area south of the city center.
Ludwigsvorstadt
•	Home to the Hauptbahnhof (Central Station) and Theresienwiese, site of Oktoberfest
•	Features a multicultural atmosphere with numerous international restaurants
Isarvorstadt
•	Known for its lively nightlife, especially in the Gärtnerplatzviertel
•	Houses the Deutsches Museum, the world's largest science and technology museum
•	Popular among young professionals and the LGBTQ+ community
This district offers a mix of entertainment, culture, and urban living, appealing to a diverse population

properties.name: Laim
properties.Description:
Laim (District 25)
•	Western district with good transport connections
•	Primarily residential with a mix of old and new buildings
•	Home to the Laimer Schlössl, a small castle from the 16th century
•	Features several parks and green spaces

properties.name: Schwabing-Freimann
properties.Description:
Schwabing-Freimann (District 12)
•	Extends north from Schwabing
•	Includes part of the English Garden
•	Home to the Allianz Arena, FC Bayern Munich's stadium
•	Features a mix of residential areas and business parks

properties.name: Moosach
properties.Description:
Moosach (District 10)
•	Northwestern district with a mix of residential and industrial areas
•	Home to the Olympia-Einkaufszentrum, a large shopping mall
•	Features the BMW Group Plant Munich
•	Offers affordable housing options compared to central districts

properties.name: Sendling
properties.Description:
Sendling (District 6)
A residential area south of the city center with a rich history.
•	Site of the Sendlinger Mordweihnacht (Sendling's Night of Murder) in 1705
•	Home to the Großmarkthalle, Munich's wholesale market for fruit and vegetables
•	Features numerous parks and green spaces
•	Offers a mix of old buildings and modern residential developments
Sendling is ideal for those seeking a quieter residential area with good amenities

properties.name: Schwanthalerhöhe
properties.Description:
Schwanthalerhöhe (District 8)
Also known as Westend, this district is located west of the city center.
•	Originally a working-class area, now increasingly gentrified
•	Home to the Verkehrszentrum (Transport Museum) and the Augustiner brewery
•	Features a diverse culinary scene with many international restaurants
•	Offers a mix of old and new residential buildings
Schwanthalerhöhe is becoming increasingly popular among young professionals and families

properties.name: Hadern
properties.Description:
Hadern (District 20)
Southwestern district, largely residential
Home to the Großhadern Clinical Center, part of the University Hospital
Mix of single-family homes and apartment buildings
Features the Westpark, a large recreational area

properties.name: Untergiesing-Harlaching
properties.Description:
Untergiesing-Harlaching (District 18)
•	Located along the eastern bank of the Isar River
•	Untergiesing: Mix of old buildings and modern developments
•	Harlaching: Affluent area with many villas and green spaces
•	Home to the Tierpark Hellabrunn, Munich's zoo

properties.name: Maxvorstadt
properties.Description:
Maxvorstadt (District 3)
Often called Munich's "Brain of the City," Maxvorstadt is the intellectual and artistic hub.
•	Home to several universities, including Ludwig Maximilian University
•	Features world-renowned museums in the Kunstareal (Art District)
•	Center of education and culture
•	Offers a vibrant café scene and numerous bookshops
Maxvorstadt is ideal for students, academics, and art enthusiasts

properties.name: Altstadt-Lehel
properties.Description:
Altstadt-Lehel (District 1)
The heart of Munich, Altstadt-Lehel encompasses the historic city center and the adjacent Lehel neighborhood.
Altstadt (Old Town)
•	Founded in 1158 by Henry the Lion
•	Home to iconic landmarks like Marienplatz, Frauenkirche, and Hofbräuhaus
•	Features pedestrian-friendly shopping areas and numerous museums
•	Bustling with tourists and locals alike
Lehel
•	One of Munich's oldest neighborhoods, formerly outside the city walls
•	Now an upscale residential area with elegant 19th-century buildings
•	Houses the Bavarian National Museum and the Haus der Kunst
This district offers a perfect blend of history, culture, and modern amenities, making it ideal for tourists and history enthusiasts

properties.name: Pasing-Obermenzing
properties.Description:
Pasing (District 21)
•	Western district with a distinct town center
•	Important transportation hub with a major railway station
•	Offers a good balance of urban amenities and green spaces
•	Home to Nymphenburg Porcelain Manufactory

properties.name: Trudering-Riem
properties.Description:
Trudering-Riem (District 15)
•	Eastern district, site of the former Munich-Riem Airport
•	Now features the Munich Trade Fair Center (Messe München)
•	Includes the Riemer Park, a large recreational area
•	Mixture of old village structures and modern developments

properties.name: Milbertshofen-Am Hart
properties.Description:
Milbertshofen-Am Hart (District 11)
•	Located in the north of Munich
•	Home to BMW's headquarters and main factory
•	Features the Olympic Park from the 1972 Summer Olympics
•	Mix of residential areas and industrial zones

properties.name: Au-Haidhausen
properties.Description:
Au-Haidhausen (District 5)
Located east of the Isar River, this district has a unique character.
Au
•	Originally a working-class neighborhood, now gentrified
•	Home to the Paulaner brewery and several beer gardens
Haidhausen
•	Known as the "French Quarter" due to its street names
•	Features the Kulturzentrum Gasteig, Munich's largest cultural center
•	Offers a mix of trendy bars, restaurants, and quiet residential areas
This district appeals to a diverse range of residents, from young professionals to families

properties.name: Ramersdorf-Perlach
properties.Description:
Ramersdorf-Perlach (District 16)
•	Large district in the southeast of Munich
•	Ramersdorf: Older part with a more traditional character
•	Neuperlach: Developed in the 1960s as a planned satellite town
•	Features large apartment complexes and green spaces
•	Home to the PEP shopping center, one of Munich's largest malls

properties.name: Allach-Untermenzing
properties.Description:
Allach-Untermenzing (District 23)
•	Northwestern district bordering the Dachau district
•	Allach: Home to a large BMW plant
•	Untermenzing: Primarily residential area
•	Features large green spaces and easy access to nature

properties.name: Thalkirchen-Obersendling-Forstenried-Fürstenried-Solln
properties.Description:
Thalkirchen-Obersendling-Forstenried-Fürstenried-Solln (District 19)
•	Large, diverse district in the south of Munich
•	Thalkirchen: Known for its recreational areas along the Isar
•	Obersendling: Former industrial area now transforming into a modern quarter
•	Forstenried and Fürstenried: Residential areas with a suburban feel
•	Solln: Upscale area with many villas and excellent views of the Alps

properties.name: Feldmoching-Hasenbergl
properties.Description:
Feldmoching-Hasenbergl (District 24)
•	Northernmost district of Munich
•	Feldmoching: Retains a village-like character with some farming
•	Hasenbergl: Developed in the 1960s as a social housing project
•	Home to the Feldmochinger See, a popular local recreation area

properties.name: Aubing-Lochhausen-Langwied
properties.Description:
Aubing-Lochhausen-Langwied (District 22)
•	Western district with a more rural character
•	Aubing is the oldest part, with a history dating back to the 8th century
•	Lochhausen and Langwied were formerly independent villages
•	Mix of old farmhouses and newer residential developments

properties.name: Bogenhausen
properties.Description:
Bogenhausen (District 13)
•	Upscale residential area east of the Isar river
•	Home to many diplomatic missions and consulates
•	Features the Prinzregententheater and Villa Stuck museum
•	Known for its elegant Art Nouveau villas and green spaces

properties.name: Obergiesing-Fasangarten
properties.Description:
Obergiesing-Fasangarten (District 17)
•	Former working-class area now undergoing gentrification
•	Known for its authentic Munich character
•	Home to TSV 1860 Munich football club and Grünwalder Stadium
•	Fasangarten: Quieter residential area with single-family homes

properties.name: Neuhausen-Nymphenburg
properties.Description:
Neuhausen-Nymphenburg (District 9)
•	Known for the baroque Nymphenburg Palace and its gardens
•	Features a mix of residential areas and local businesses
•	Home to the Hirschgarten, Munich's largest beer garden
•	Offers a high quality of life with numerous green spaces
